ğŸ§  What is Event Handling in React?

Event handling in React is used to **respond to user actions**, such as:

* Clicking a button
* Typing in an input
* Submitting a form
* Hovering over elements

ğŸ“Œ React uses **camelCase** for event names.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”¤ HTML vs React Events

| HTML     | React    |
| -------- | -------- |
| onclick  | onClick  |
| onchange | onChange |
| onsubmit | onSubmit |

ğŸ“Œ React uses camelCase
ğŸ“Œ Pass function, not string

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Basic Event Handling Example

```jsx
function App() {
  function handleClick() {
    alert("Button Clicked");
  }

  return <button onClick={handleClick}>Click Me</button>;
}
```

âœ” Pass function reference
âŒ `onClick="handleClick()"`

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”¹ Inline Event Handler

```jsx
<button onClick={() => alert("Clicked")}>
  Click
</button>
```

ğŸ“Œ Useful for small logic
âš  Avoid complex inline functions

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”·Event Handling with State

```jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
      {count}
    </button>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Event updates state
ğŸ“Œ State change â†’ Re-render

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Handling Input Events

```jsx
function InputExample() {
  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  return (
    <input 
      type="text"
      value={name}
      onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ `e.target.value` gets input value
ğŸ“Œ Controlled component

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Handling Form Submit

```jsx
function FormExample() {
  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    alert("Form Submitted");
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Always use `preventDefault()`
ğŸ“Œ Prevents page reload

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  Synthetic Events in React

React wraps browser events into **SyntheticEvent**.

âœ” Cross-browser compatible
âœ” Same API across all browsers

Example:

```jsx
function handleClick(event) {
  console.log(event.type);
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Passing Arguments in Events

```jsx
<button onClick={() => handleClick("Saakshi")}>
  Click
</button>
```

ğŸ“Œ Use arrow function to pass parameters

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ Event Handling in Class Components

```jsx
class Button extends React.Component {
  handleClick = () => {
    alert("Clicked");
  };

  render() {
    return <button onClick={this.handleClick}>Click</button>;
  }
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Bind methods properly
ğŸ“Œ Arrow functions auto-bind `this`

